  "doc_id": "7944",
  "text": "The fluctuating resource hypothesis states that an increase in unused resources enhances plant community susceptibility to biological invasion [CITATION_1] . On the other hand, invasive plants are often characterized by a more rapid growth and reproduction compared to native plants [CITATION_2] ), a competitive ability to modify the invaded environment (e.g., by allelochemical production - [CITATION_3] , and a phenotypic plasticity allowing adaptation to a wide range of environmental conditions [CITATION_4] . Established invaders, in addition, can actively modify resource dynamics by altering the soil nutrient cycle, thus leading to plant-soil feedback fostering invader success [CITATION_5] .",
